qas.question: Who does the Federal Reserve have to place an order with for printed money?
Who can freely withdraw from  their reserve accounts at the Federal Reserve?
Who do the reserve accounts have to place an order with for printed money?
Who can freely withdraw from their Federal Reserve accounts at the Bureau of Engraving and Printing?

context: When the <a0_0>Federal Reserve<a0_0/> makes a purchase, it credits the seller's reserve account (with the Federal Reserve). This money is not transferred from any existing funds—it is at this point that the <b5_0>Federal Reserve<b5_0/> has created new high-powered money. <a4_0><b9_0>Commercial banks<b9_0/><a4_0/> can freely withdraw in cash any excess reserves from their reserve account at the Federal Reserve. To fulfill those requests, the Federal Reserve places an order for printed money from the <a1_0><b6_0>U.S. Treasury Department<b6_0/><a1_0/>. The Treasury Department in turn sends these requests to the Bureau of <a3_0><b8_0>Engraving and Printing<b8_0/><a3_0/> (to print new dollar bills) and the <a2_0><b7_0>Bureau of the Mint<b7_0/><a2_0/> (to stamp the coins).
